quran[29]{c,v,t,f}:
81,1,"When the sun shall be folded up, {1}",footnotes:1:This is a matchless metaphor for causing the sun to lose its light. Takwir means to fold up; hence takwir al-amamah is used for folding up the turban on the head. Here
81,2,"when the stars shall scatter away, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
81,3,"when the mountains shall be set in motion, {1}",footnotes:1:In other words
81,4,"when the ten-months pregnant camels shall be abandoned, {1}",footnotes:1:This was by far the best way of giving an idea of the severities and horrors of Resurrection to the Arabs. Before the buses and trucks of the present day there was nothing more precious for the Arabs than the she-camel just about to give birth to her young. In this state she was most sedulously looked after and cared for
81,5,"when the savage beasts shall be brought together, {1}",footnotes:1:When a general calamity befalls the world
81,6,"when the seas shall be set boiling, {1}",footnotes:1:The word sujjirat as used in the original in passive voice from tasjir in the past tense. Tasjir means to kindle fire in the oven. Apparently it seems strange that on the Resurrection Day fire would blaze up in the oceans. But if the truth about water is kept in view
81,7,"when {1} the souls shall be rejoined (with their bodies), {2}",footnotes:1:From here begins mention of the second stage of Resurrection.That is
81,8,"and when the girl-child buried alive shall be asked:"
81,9,"for what offence was she killed? {1}",footnotes:1:The style of this verse reflects an intensity of rage and fury inconceivable in common life. The parents who buried their daughters alive
81,10,"and when the scrolls of (men's) deeds shall be unfolded,"
81,11,"and when Heaven is laid bare; {1}",footnotes:1:That is
81,12,"and Hell is stoked,"
81,13,"and Paradise brought nigh: {1}",footnotes:1:That is
81,14,"then shall each person know what he has brought along."
81,15,"No indeed; {1} I swear by the alternating stars",footnotes:1:That is
81,16,"that hide,"
81,17,"and by the night as it recedes,"
81,18,"and the morn as it breathes. {1}",footnotes:1:That for which the oath has been sworn
81,19,"Verily this is the word of a noble message-bearer; {1}",footnotes:1:A noble messenger: the Angel who brought down revelation
81,20,"one mighty {1} and held in honour with the Lord of the Throne;",footnotes:1:(Surah An-Najm
81,21,"there he is obeyed {1} and held trustworthy. {2}",footnotes:1:That is
81,22,"(O people of Makkah), your companion {1} is not mad;",footnotes:1:Your Companion: the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him). Here
81,23,"he indeed saw the message-bearer on the clear horizon; {1}",footnotes:1:(In Surah An-Najm
81,24,"nor does he grudge (conveying this knowledge about) the Unseen; {1}",footnotes:1:That is
81,25,"nor is it a word of an accursed Satan. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
81,26,"Where to are you then heading?"
81,27,"It is nothing but Good Counsel for everyone in the world,"
81,28,"for everyone of you who wishes to follow the Straight Way; {1}",footnotes:1:In other words
81,29,"but your wishing will not avail unless Allah, the Lord of the Universe, so wishes. {1}",footnotes:1:This theme has already occurred in   (Surah Al- Muddaththir
